  "prompt": "How many colors and hues are distinguishable to the human eye?",
  "response": "The human eye can distinguish about 1 million different colors. This ability comes from the presence of three types of cone cells in the retina, which are sensitive to different wavelengths of light corresponding to the colors red, green, and blue. The combination of signals from these cones allows us to perceive a wide spectrum of hues.\n\nWhile there isn't a strict upper limit to the number of distinguishable colors, some estimates suggest that depending on factors like lighting conditions, context, and individual differences, the human eye could potentially differentiate up to 10 million hues under optimal conditions. However, in practical terms, people are generally able to consistently identify and name a much smaller set of colors, with many shades and variations falling into broader categories.",
